section
	h1 Random Experiments
	dl 
		dt: dfn Random experiment 
		dd 
			p A process by which we observe something uncertain #[span.example before rolling a die you do not know the result]. #[mark After the experiment, the result of the random experiment is known].
			p When we repeat a random experiment several times, we call each one of them a #[dfn trial] - a particular performance of a random experiment #[span.example when tossing a coin, each trial will result in either heads or tails].
		dt: dfn Outcome
		dd 
			p A result of a random experiment.
		dt: dfn Sample space
		dd
			p The set of all possible outcomes. Thus in the context of a random experiment, the sample space is our #[dfn universal set]. #[mark The sample space is defined based on how you define your random experiment].
			figure.example
				+m.block S = \{ (H,H,H), (H,H,T), (H,T,H), (T,H,H), (H,T,T),(T,H,T),(T,T,H),(T,T,T) \}
				figcaption The sample space of random experiment: tossing a coin three times and observing the sequence of heads/tails.
			figure.example
				+m.block S = \{ (H), (T) \}
				figcaption The sample space of random experiment: tossing a coin one time and observing the sequence of heads/tails.
	figure.example
		ul
			li Random experiment: toss a coin; sample space: #[+m S=\{heads, tails\}] or as we usually write it, #[+m \{H,T\}].
			li Random experiment: roll a die; sample space: #[+m S=\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}].
			li Random experiment: observe the number of iPhones sold by an Apple store in Boston in #[+m 2015]; sample space: #[+m S=\{0, 1, 2, 3, \cdots \}].
			li Random experiment: observe the number of goals in a soccer match; sample space: #[+m S=\{0, 1, 2, 3, \cdots \}].
